• Employed when the theoretical analysis is diﬃcult.
• Aim:
• formulation of an hypothesis regarding the algorithm eﬃciency;
• veriﬁcation of this hypothesis;
• comparison of algorithms;
• eﬃciency analysis of some implementation.

• recursive algorithms: easy to implement;
• additional cost: each recursive call places information in a speciﬁc
memory zone (program stack).

• direct
• starts from the base case and builds successive terms using the
recurrence;
• the expression of the general term T (n) is identiﬁed;
• it is proved by direct computations or mathematical induction.
• reverse
• it starts from the T (n) and is replaced by T (h(n)) with corresponding
value, then T (h(h(n))) is replaced and so on until the base case is
reached;
• T (n) is obtained.
